      "u_gold": "To find creative, practical shelter solutions for harsh winter conditions, you should assemble a diverse team of experts with the following skillsets:\n\n1. Structural Engineer: A structural engineer will be responsible for ensuring the structural integrity and security of the shelters. They will design structures that can withstand the weight of snow, wind, and other extreme weather conditions.\n2. Architect: An architect will focus on the aesthetics, functionality, and layout of the shelters. They will ensure that the shelters are not only practical but also comfortable and efficient for the users.\n3. Materials Scientist: A materials scientist will evaluate and recommend appropriate materials for the shelters, considering factors such as thermal properties, durability, and cost. They will play a crucial role in ensuring the shelters are energy-efficient and adequately insulated.\n4. Climatologist or Meteorologist: A climatologist or meteorologist will provide information on the specific weather conditions in the area, helping the team to design shelters that can withstand extreme temperatures, wind, and snowfall.\n5. Construction Manager: A construction manager will be responsible for overseeing the construction process and ensuring that the shelters are built within budget and on schedule. They will also manage communication between the team and the contractors.\n6. Cost Engineer: A cost engineer will estimate the cost of materials, labor, and other resources required for the construction and maintenance of the shelters. They will help to find ways to minimize costs without compromising the quality and functionality of the shelters.\n7. Environmental Specialist: An environmental specialist will evaluate the potential impact of the shelters on the local ecosystem and recommend ways to minimize the environmental footprint. They will also ensure that the construction process follows all relevant regulations and guidelines.\n8. End-user Representati