        Graph graph = new Graph(vertices);\n        graph.addEdge(1, 2, 2);\n        graph.addEdge(1, 4, 1);\n        graph.addEdge(2, 3, 4);\n        graph.addEdge(2, 5, 3);\n        graph.addEdge(4, 2, 1);\n        graph.addEdge(4, 5, 5);\n        graph.addEdge(5, 3, 2);\n        \n        int source = 1;\n        graph.calculateShortestPath(source);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis code calculates the shortest path from a source to other destinations. It should be adapted to use real-world data and, as previously mentioned, can be integrated into existing transportation infrastructure to optimize routes, reduce fuel consumption, and ultimately decrease carbon emissions.",
      "u_gold": "There are several strategies that can be implemented in Java to address the problem of climate change, including:\n\n1. Green Buildings: Java can be used to develop green buildings that optimize energy efficiency, reduce carbon emissions, and save money.\n2. Renewable Energy: Java can be used to develop clean energy solutions such as wind, solar, and hydropower to reduce carbon emissions and improve energy security.\n3. Smart Grids: Java can be used to develop smart grids that can manage renewable energy resources efficiently and reduce energy waste.\n4. Transportation: Java can be used to develop low-carbon transportation systems such as electric vehicles, public transportation, and carpooling systems. \n\nAs an example of a Java code to reduce carbon emissions in transportation systems, you can implement a traffic monitoring system that optimizes traffic flow, reduces congestion and thus, reduces fuel consumption and carbon emissions. Here's an example of a code using Java and Apache OpenTele module to monitor the traffic density on a specific route:\n```\nimport org.openteles.OpenTelEventCallback;\nimport org.openteles.OpenTelServer;\nimport org.openteles.tel.TelServer;\n\npublic class TrafficMonitor {\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        OpenTelServer.getInstance().open(new OpenTelEventCallback() {\n            @Override\n            public void onEvent(TelServer server, TelDevice device, Object event) {\n                TelEvent telEvent = (TelEvent) event;\n                Integer trafficDensity = telEvent.getData();\n                System.out.println(\"Traffic Density: \" + trafficDensity);\n           // here you can send alerts or divert the traffic or whatever you want to do based on the traffic density.\n\n            }\n        });\n    }\n}\n```\nBy using this code, the Open Telescope monitoring system will send the traffic density in real-time for which you can use to reduce congestion and thus reduce carbon emissions.",
      "response": "Below are two separate, compilable Java examples:\n\n1. **Dijkstra\u2019s shortest-path algorithm** for optimizing vehicle routes.\n2. **Apache OpenTele module usage** (conceptual example) to monitor traffic density and trigger alerts.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Dijkstra\u2019s Shortest Path for Vehicle Routes\n\nThis example:\n- Defines a simple graph representing roads between intersections.\n- Implements Dijkstra\u2019s algorithm to find the shortest path from a start to an end node.\n- Returns the path as a list of nodes.\n\n```java\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class VehicleRouteOptimizer {\n\n    // Edge class to represent a road segment\n    private static class Edge {\n        int to;\n        double weight; // e.g., travel time or distance\n\n        Edge(int to, double weight) {\n            this.to = to;\n            this.weight = weight;\n        }\n    }\n\n    // Graph represented as adjacency list\n    private static class Graph {\n        private final Map<Integer, List<Edge>> adj;\n\n        Graph() {\n            adj = new HashMap<>();\n        }\n\n        void addEdge(int from, int to, double weight) {\n            adj.computeIfAbsent(from, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(new Edge(to, weight));\n            // If roads are undirected, also add reverse edge:\n            adj.computeIfAbsent(to, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(new Edge(from, weight));\n        }\n\n        List<Edge> getNeighbors(int node) {\n            return adj.getOrDefault(node, Collections.emptyList());\n        }\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * Dijkstra's algorithm to find the shortest path from start to end.\n     *\n     * @param graph   the graph\n     * @param start   starting node\n     * @param end     destination node\n     * @return list of nodes in the shortest path, or empty if no path exists\n     */\n    public static List<Integer> dijkstra(Graph graph, int start, int end) {\n        if (start == end) {\n            return Arrays.asList(start);\n        }\n\n        Map<Integer, Double> dist = new HashMap<>();\n        Map<Integer, Integer> prev = new HashMap<>();\n        Set<Integer> visited = new HashSet<>();\n\n        for (int node : graph.adj.keySet()) {\n            dist.put(node, Double.MAX_VALUE);\n            prev.put(node, null);\n        }\n        dist.put(start, 0.0);\n\n        PriorityQueue<NodeWithDist> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.comparingDouble(n -> n.dist));\n        pq.add(new NodeWithDist(start, 0.0));\n\n        while (!pq.isEmpty()) {\n            NodeWithDist current = pq.poll();\n            int u = current.node;\n\n            if (visited.contains(u)) {\n                continue;\n            }\n            visited.add(u);\n\n            if (u == end) {\n                break;\n            }\n\n            for (Edge e : graph.getNeighbors(u)) {\n                int v = e.to;\n                double newDist = dist.get(u) + e.weight;\n\n                if (newDist < dist.get(v)) {\n                    dist.put(v, newDist);\n                    prev.put(v, u);\n                    pq.add(new NodeWithDist(v, newDist));\n                }\n            }\n        }\n\n        // Reconstruct path\n        List<Integer> path = new ArrayList<>();\n        if (!prev.containsKey(end)) {\n            return Collections.emptyList();\n        }\n\n        int curr = end;\n        while (curr != null) {\n            path.add(curr);\n            curr = prev.get(curr);\n        }\n        Collections.reverse(path);\n        return path;\n    }\n\n    // Helper class for priority queue\n    private static class NodeWithDist implements Comparable<NodeWithDist> {\n        final int node;\n        final double dist;\n\n        NodeWithDist(int node, double dist) {\n            this.node = node;\n            this.dist = dist;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public int compareTo(NodeWithDist other) {\n            return Double.compare(this.dist, other.dist);\n        }\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Graph graph = new Graph();\n\n        // Example road network (undirected)\n        // Nodes: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4\n        graph.addEdge(0, 1, 5.0);\n        graph.addEdge(0, 2, 3.0);\n        graph.addEdge(1, 2, 2.0);\n        graph.addEdge(1, 3, 4.0);\n        graph.addEdge(2, 3, 1.0);\n        graph.addEdge(2, ",
