      "s_instruction": "Provide a complete, step-by-step implementation guide including the exact code for the gRPC service, client, and SMTP logic using MailKit.",
      "u_instruction": "Provide a high-level overview of the steps required to build the service and client, listing the key files to create without providing the full implementation code.",
      "s_gold": "For creating a small .NET microservice that sends emails through SMTP and is consumed by other services using gRPC, follow the steps below.\n\nStep 1: Create the Email Service using .NET and gRPC\n1. Create a new .NET gRPC Service by running the following command in your terminal or command prompt:\n```\ndotnet new grpc -o EmailService\n```\n2. Add `MailKit` NuGet package to your project `EmailService.csproj` for handling email sending via SMTP:\n```\n<PackageReference Include=\"MailKit\" Version=\"2.15.0\" />\n```\n3. Define a \"SendEmail\" service in the `Protos\\emailservice.proto`:\n```proto\nsyntax = \"proto3\";\n\noption csharp_namespace = \"EmailService\";\n\npackage emailservice;\n\nservice Email {\n  rpc Send (EmailRequest) returns (EmailResponse);\n}\n\nmessage EmailRequest {\n  string from = 1;\n  string to = 2;\n  string subject = 3;\n  string body = 4;\n}\n\nmessage EmailResponse {\n  bool success = 1;\n  string message = 2;\n}\n```\n4. Implement the `Email` service in the `Services\\EmailService.cs`:\n```csharp\nusing System.Threading.Tasks;\nusing Grpc.Core;\nusing EmailService;\nusing MailKit.Net.Smtp;\nusing MimeKit;\n\npublic class EmailSenderService : Email.EmailBase\n{\n    public override async Task<EmailResponse> Send(EmailRequest request, ServerCallContext context)\n    {\n        var message = new MimeMessage();\n        message.From.Add(new MailboxAddress(request.From));\n        message.To.Add(new MailboxAddress(request.To));\n        message.Subject = request.Subject;\n\n        message.Body = new TextPart(\"plain\") { Text = request.Body };\n\n        try\n        {\n            using var client = new SmtpClient();\n            await client.ConnectAsync(\"smtp.example.com\", 587, false);\n            client.AuthenticationMechanisms.Remove(\"XOAUTH2\"); // Disabling XOAUTH2 for testing purposes\n            await client.AuthenticateAsync(\"username\", \"password\");\n            await client.SendAsync(message);\n            await client.DisconnectAsync(true);\n        }\n        catch (Exception ex)\n        {\n            return new EmailResponse { Success = false, Message = ex.Message };\n        }\n\n        return new EmailResponse { Success = true, Message = \"Email sent successfully\" };\n    }\n}\n```\nReplace `\"smtp.example.com\"`, `\"username\"`, and `\"password\"` with your SMTP credentials.\n\nStep 2: Consume the Email Service from another .NET service\n1. Create a new .NET Console project by running the following command:\n```\ndotnet new console -o EmailConsumer\n```\n2. Add gRPC-generated code from your `EmailService`.\n3. Add the NuGet packages `Google.Protobuf`, `Grpc.Net.Client`, and `Grpc.Tools` to your project's `EmailConsumer.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Google.Protobuf\" Version=\"3.19.1\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Grpc.Net.Client\" Version=\"2.41.0\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Grpc.Tools\" Version=\"2.41.0\" PrivateAssets=\"All\" />\n```\n4. Consume the gRPC Email service from your `EmailConsumer` project by using the following code in `Program.cs`:\n```csharp\nusing System;\nusing System.Threading.Tasks;\nusing EmailService;\nusing Grpc.Core;\nusing Grpc.Net.Client;\n\nclass Program\n{\n    static async Task Main()\n    {\n        var channel = GrpcChannel.ForAddress(\"https://localhost:5001\"); // Replace with the actual email service address\n        var client = new Email.EmailClient(channel);\n\n        var emailRequest = new EmailRequest\n        {\n            From = \"youremail@example.com\",\n            To = \"recipient@example.com\",\n            Subject = \"Test email\",\n            Body = \"This is a test email sent using gRPC.\"\n        };\n\n        var response = await client.SendAsync(emailRequest);\n\n        if (response.Success)\n        {\n            Console.WriteLine(\"Email sent successfully!\");\n        }\n        else\n        {\n            Console.WriteLine($\"Error sending email: {response.Message}\");\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\nReplace `https://localhost:5001` with the actual EmailService's address.\n\nNow, you have created a small .NET microservice to send emails through SMTP and consumed it using gRPC. Make sure to run both the EmailService and EmailConsumer projects to test your implementation.",
      "u_gold": "To create a lightweight .NET microservice that sends an email through SMTP using gRPC, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. Create a new gRPC project.\n2. Define the service in a .proto file.\n3. Implement the service in a .NET class.\n4. Host the service with a gRPC server.\n5. Consume the service from another .NET project.\n\nHere's an example of each step:\n\n1. Create a new gRPC project:\n```sh\ndotnet new grpc -o EmailService\ncd EmailService\n```\n1. Define the service in a .proto file:\n\nCreate a new file called \"email.proto\" in the \"Protos\" folder and add the following code:\n```proto\nsyntax = \"proto3\";\n\npackage email;\n\nservice EmailService {\n  rpc SendEmail (EmailRequest) returns (EmailResponse);\n}\n\nmessage EmailRequest {\n  string from = 1;\n  string to = 2;\n  string subject = 3;\n  string body = 4;\n}\n\nmessage EmailResponse {\n  bool success = 1;\n}\n```\n1. Implement the service in a .NET class:\n\nCreate a new file called \"EmailServiceImpl.cs\" and add the following code:\n```csharp\nusing System;\nusing System.Net.Mail;\nusing System.Threading.Tasks;\nusing Grpc.Core;\nusing email;\n\nnamespace EmailService\n{\n    public class EmailServiceImpl : EmailService.EmailServiceBase\n    {\n        private readonly string SmtpServer = \"your_smtp_server\";\n        private readonly int SmtpPort = 587;\n        private readonly string SmtpUsername = \"your_username\";\n        private readonly string SmtpPassword = \"your_password\";\n\n        public override async Task<EmailResponse> SendEmail(EmailRequest request, ServerCallContext context)\n        {\n            try\n            {\n                using (var client = new SmtpClient(SmtpServer, SmtpPort))\n                {\n                    client.Credentials = new System.Net.NetworkCredential(SmtpUsername, SmtpPassword);\n                    client.EnableSsl = true;\n\n                    var mailMessage = new MailMessage(request.From, request.To, request.Subject, request.Body);\n                    await client.SendMailAsync(mailMessage);\n\n                    return new EmailResponse { Success = true };\n                }\n            }\n            catch (Exception)\n            {\n                return new EmailResponse { Success = false };\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n1. Host the service with a gRPC server:\n\nCreate a new file called \"Startup.cs\" and add the following code:\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Builder;\nusing Microsoft.AspNetCore.Hosting;\nusing Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;\nusing Grpc.Core;\nusing Grpc.Core.Services;\nusing email;\n\nnamespace EmailService\n{\n    public class Startup\n    {\n        public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)\n        {\n            services.AddGrpc();\n        }\n\n        public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)\n        {\n            app.UseRouting();\n\n            app.UseEndpoints(endpoints =>\n            {\n                endpoints.MapGrpcService<EmailServiceImpl>();\n            });\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n1. Consume the service from another .NET project:\n\nCreate a new gRPC client project called \"EmailServiceClient\" and add the following code to send an email:\n```csharp\nusing System;\nusing System.Threading.Tasks;\nusing Grpc.Net.Client;\nusing email;\n\nnamespace EmailServiceClient\n{\n    class Program\n    {\n        static async Task Main(string[] args)\n        {\n            using var channel = GrpcChannel.ForAddress(\"https://your-email-service-url\");\n            var client = new EmailService.EmailServiceClient(channel);\n\n            var request = new EmailRequest\n            {\n                From = \"your_from_email\",\n                To = \"your_to_email\",\n                Subject = \"Test email subject\",\n                Body = \"Test email body\"\n            };\n\n            try\n            {\n                var response = await client.SendEmailAsync(request);\n                Console.WriteLine($",
      "response": "Here is a high-level overview of the steps required to build a gRPC service that sends emails via SMTP using MailKit, along with the key files you need to create.\n\n### Prerequisites\nBefore creating files, ensure you have the following installed:\n*   **.NET SDK** (e.g., .NET 6 or .NET 8).\n*   **NuGet Packages**:\n    *   `Grpc.Net.Client` (for the client)\n    *   `Grpc.Net.ClientFactory`\n    *   `MailKit` (for SMTP logic)\n    *   `System.Text.Json` (for configuration)\n\n---\n\n### Step 1: Define the gRPC Interface\nYou need to define the contract for the email service. This file describes the methods the server will implement and the client will call.\n\n**Key File to Create:**\n*   `EmailService.proto`\n    *   Define a service named `EmailService`.\n    *   Define a method `SendEmail` that takes a `SendEmailRequest` (containing `To`, `From`, `Subject`, `Body`) and returns a `SendEmailResponse` (containing `Status` and `Message`).\n\n### Step 2: Generate gRPC Code\nYou must generate C# classes from the `.proto` file. This creates the stubs for the client and the interface for the server.\n\n**Action:**\n*   Run the `dotnet grpc_tools.protoc` command or use the Visual Studio \"Add Service\" wizard.\n*   **Output Files Generated:**\n    *   `EmailService.cs` (Server interface)\n    *   `EmailServiceClient.cs` (Client stub)\n    *   `EmailServiceGrpc.cs` (Internal gRPC implementation details)\n\n### Step 3: Implement the gRPC Server\nCreate the logic that handles incoming requests and performs the actual SMTP sending.\n\n**Key File to Create:**\n*   `EmailServiceServer.cs`\n    *   Implement the `EmailService` interface defined in Step 1.\n    *   Inside the `SendEmail` method:\n        1.  Instantiate a `MailKit.Net.Smtp.SmtpClient`.\n        2.  Configure the SMTP server, port, username, and password.\n        3.  Use `MailKit` to send the email (handling headers and body encoding).\n        4.  Return the success status to the gRPC caller.\n\n### Step 4: Implement the gRPC Client\nCreate the logic for the application that needs to send emails via the service.\n\n**Key File to Create:**\n*   `EmailClient.cs`\n    *   Inject the `EmailServiceClient` (from Step 2) via constructor injection.\n    *   Create a method `SendEmailAsync(string to, string from, string subject, string body)`.\n    *   Inside this method:\n        1.  Create a `SendEmailRequest` object.\n        2.  Call the `SendEmail` method on the client stub.\n        3.  Handle the response and log any errors.\n\n### Step 5: Configure the Application\nYou need a way to manage credentials and settings without hardcoding them in the code.\n\n**Key File to Create:**\n*   `appsettings.json`\n    *   Add sections for `SmtpSettings` (Server, Port, Username, Password) and `GrpcSettings` (Endpoint URL).\n*   `Program.cs` (or `Startup.cs`)\n    *   **Server Setup**: Register the `EmailServiceServer` with the gRPC middleware.\n    *   **Client Setup**: Register the `EmailServiceClientFactory` and configure the endpoint.\n    *   **Dependency Injection**: Register the `SmtpClient` (from MailKit) as a singleton or scoped service to reuse the connection.\n\n### Summary of File Structure\nYour project will look like this:\n\n```text\nYourProject/\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 EmailService.proto          # 1. Protocol definition\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 EmailService.cs             # 2. Generated Server Interface\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 EmailServiceClient.cs       # 2. Generated Client Stub\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 EmailServiceServer.cs       # 3. Server Implementation (SMTP Logic)\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 EmailClient.cs              # 4. Client Implementation\n\u251c\u2500\u2500 appsettings.json            # 5. Configuration\n\u2514\u2500\u2500 Program.cs                  # 5. Entry point & DI Setup\n```\n",
