      "s_gold": "Dear Editor,\nThank you for taking the time to review my manuscript and provide feedback. I appreciate your attention to detail and am grateful for your insights. I understand that there were issues with chemical notations and the analytical and sampling methods in my manuscript, including incorrect super and subscripts, wrong order, and ambiguous descriptions of the methods used. I will work carefully to ensure that all chemical notations are accurate and that the analytical and sampling methods are thoroughly described in future submissions. Additionally, I will review my calculations to ensure that my formulas are accurate and that the parameters are clearly defined. I will also make sure to proofread and correct any typos. I look forward to submitting a revised manuscript in the future, and hope that these improvements will make my research more accessible and valuable to the scientific community.",
      "u_gold": "Dear Editor,\n\nThank you for taking the time to review our manuscript and for providing constructive feedback. We acknowledge the shortcomings in our submission, particularly the issues regarding chemical notations, analytical and sampling methods, as well as typos.\n\nWe understand the necessity of correcting these errors and providing clearer explanations to ensure the accuracy and credibility of our research. We plan to revise the manuscript by addressing each of the concerns you have raised. Specifically, we will:\n\n1. Thoroughly review and correct all chemical notations, ensuring the correct use of super and subscripts, as well as the appropriate order of elements.\n2. Revisit our use of flame photometry and, if necessary, justify our assumptions or alternatively employ a more suitable analytical method for determining ion concentrations.\n3. Elaborate on the sampling and analytical methods used in our study, including descriptions of QA/QC protocols, blanks, sample conservation, and filtration methods.\n4. Correct the inconsistency in referring to the % Na parameter as soluble sodium and revise Equation 5 to accurately represent the relationship between sodium and potassium.\n5. Meticulously proofread the manuscript to identify and correct any typos, including the one in Figure 1.\n6. Adopt the practice of using significant digits in numbers, ensuring a more appropriate representation of the data.\n\nWe believe that addressing these issues will greatly enhance the quality and clarity of our manuscript, and we are eager to resubmit a revised version for your consideration. We appreciate your guidance and the opportunity to refine our work, and we look forward to your feedback on the revised manuscript.\n\nSincerely,\n\n[Your Name]\n\n[Your Affiliation]",
      "response": "### Option 1: Polite Letter to the Editor (Acknowledging Rejection)\n\n**Subject:** Response to Recent Submission: [Manuscript Title]\n\nDear Editor [Editor's Last Name],\n\nI am writing to formally acknowledge the decision regarding my recent submission, \"[Manuscript Title],\" (Manuscript ID: [ID Number]). While I was disappointed to learn that the manuscript will not be accepted for publication at this time, I sincerely appreciate the time and effort you and your team have dedicated to reviewing my work.\n\nI understand that the decision was based on the current state of the manuscript and the specific criteria outlined in your review. I take full responsibility for any shortcomings identified and will ensure that these issues are thoroughly addressed in my future submissions. My goal is to maintain the high standards of quality and rigor that your journal upholds.\n\nThank you again for your constructive feedback and for considering my work. I look forward to the opportunity to submit a revised and improved manuscript in the future.\n\nSincerely,\n\n[Your Name]  \n[Your Affiliation]  \n[Your Contact Information]\n\n***\n\n### Option 2: Formal Cover Letter (Addressing Specific Critiques)\n\n**Subject:** Revised Submission: [Manuscript Title] (Response to Reviewer Comments)\n\nDear Editor [Editor's Last Name],\n\nPlease find attached our revised manuscript, \"[Manuscript Title],\" which we are submitting for consideration in *[Journal Name]*. We are grateful for the opportunity to resubmit this work following the constructive feedback provided in the recent decision letter and reviewer comments.\n\nWe have carefully reviewed every point raised by the reviewers and the editorial team. Below is a summary of the specific, actionable steps we have taken to address the critiques:\n\n*   **Regarding [Critique 1: e.g., Methodological clarity]:** We have expanded the \"Methods\" section to explicitly detail the statistical protocols used. Additionally, we have added a new subsection describing the validation process to ensure reproducibility.\n*   **Regarding [Critique 2: e.g., Literature gap]:** We have conducted a comprehensive review of recent literature published since our initial submission. Three key studies have been added to the Introduction and Discussion sections to contextualize our findings within the current state of the field.\n*   **Regarding [Critique 3: e.g., Data interpretation]:** We have re-analyzed the data to support the new claims made in the Results section. The revised figures now include error bars and confidence intervals to better illustrate the significance of the trends observed.\n*   **Regarding [Critique 4: e.g., Scope/Feasibility]:** We have refined the scope of the study to align more closely with the journal's focus, removing the supplementary analysis that fell outside the primary objectives.\n\nA point-by-point response to the reviewers' comments is included as a separate document attached to this submission. We believe these revisions significantly strengthen the manuscript and address the concerns raised.\n\nThank you for your time and consideration of this revised version. We look forward to your response.\n\nSincerely,\n\n[Your Name]  \n[Your Title/Affiliation]  \n[Your Contact Information]\n",
