      "s_instruction": "Write a structured, third-person summary of a fictional character's phobia, detailing the backstory, physical/emotional reactions, and treatment history in a detached, expository style.",
      "u_instruction": "Write a continuous, third-person narrative in present tense depicting a character experiencing a phobia in real-time, focusing on immediate sensory details and the moment-by-moment progression of their anxiety.",
      "s_gold": "I understand, and I will do my best to provide a helpful and respectful response.\nThe protagonist of this personal experience with a phobia is a young woman named Sarah. Sarah has suffered from a severe phobia of enclosed spaces since she was a child. The phobia stems from a traumatic experience when Sarah was on a family vacation in an amusement park. She was accidentally locked in a small, enclosed space with no way out. The experience left her feeling terrified and helpless, and the fear has persisted ever since.\nAs an adult, Sarah finds herself constantly on edge, anxious about being in any situation where she might feel trapped or unable to escape. She avoids elevators, small rooms, and crowded places at all costs. The physical reactions include a racing heart, sweating, and an overwhelming sense of panic. Emotionally, Sarah feels like she is constantly walking on eggshells, trying to avoid any situation that might trigger her phobia.\nDespite her best efforts, Sarah has tried various treatments and coping mechanisms to manage her phobia. She has attended therapy sessions, practiced deep breathing exercises, and even tried medication. However, the phobia remains a constant presence in her life, making everyday activities difficult and stressful.\nIn an attempt to help Sarah confront her fear, her therapist suggested that she expose herself gradually to the stimulus that triggers her phobia. The therapist created a safe and controlled environment, starting with small, manageable steps. Sarah was asked to enter a small room with a trusted friend or family member, gradually increasing the time spent in the room.\nAs Sarah entered the room, her heart raced, and she felt her palms grow sweaty. She could feel her panic rising, threatening to consume her. However, with the support of her loved one and the therapist, Sarah took slow, deep breaths and focusing on the present moment. She visualized a sunny day, a calming sensation that helped to soothe her nerves.\nThe experience was challenging, but with each subsequent step, Sarah found that her fear began to dissipate. She realized that she had the power to confront her phobia and reclaim her life.\nThrough this narrative, I hope to convey the physical and emotional intensity of a phobic reaction and the resilience of the human spirit in overcoming fear. The experience of Sarah is a testament to the power of therapy and support in managing phobias. By facing her fear head-on and creating a safe and controlled environment, Sarah was able to take back control of her life and live without the constant burden of her phobia.",
      "u_gold": "As Sarah walks through the park, she hears a cough. It's not a loud cough, but it's enough to make her heart race and her palms get sweaty. She knows that it's time to implement her coping mechanism.\n\nSarah's phobia began when she was six years old, visiting her grandmother for the first time. Grandma had a terrible cough, and Sarah was scared. Since then, she's had an intense fear of coughs. It's so severe that even a fake cough or sneeze can make her panic.\n\nAs she starts to feel the anxiety wash over her, Sarah closes her eyes and takes slow, deep breaths. The fragrance of the blooming flowers mixed with the fresh, clean air does nothing to soothe her racing thoughts. She focuses on the physical sensations, feeling the sun warming her face and the grass below her feet.\n\nShe's learned that if she can get control of her breathing, she can avoid a full-blown panic attack. As she takes a few more deep breaths, she feels a little calmer. A family with a small child comes into view, and the girl gives a loud sneeze that reverberates above the chirping birds.\n\nSarah instantly feels her heart rate escalate again, anticipating another loud sound. She reminds herself that this is just her fear, that it doesn't have to rule her. As she walks on, she tries to distract herself with the scenery, gazing at the shady trees and colorful flowers.\n\nShe remembers the therapy she's gone to, how the therapist had tried to make her face her fear by exposing her to different types of cough sounds, gradually increasing the intensity. It had helped her a little, but panic attacks still happen.\n\nNow, she gropes for her pocket, and clenches the smooth stone that she always keeps there. It serves as a physical anchor, giving her something tangible to focus on when her mind is racing. She holds it tightly, letting the cool surface calm her.\n\nAs Sarah continues her walk, she still hears the occasional cough, but she can now manage her panic. She feels a sense of pride in her ability to stay in control, to face her fear. She knows that this battle will never be over, but with every step she feels stronger, more grounded.",
      "response": "The air in the waiting room shifts, a subtle change in pressure that Elias feels before his eyes register the source. A single, unassuming door stands slightly ajar, its frame painted a stark, clinical white that seems to absorb the dim light of the room. Elias's breath hitches, a shallow, ragged intake that tastes of copper and stale air. His heart begins its frantic drumming, a rhythmic thud against his ribs that quickly escalates into a chaotic pounding, syncing with the rapid flutter of his own hands.\n\nHe takes a step forward, his boots squeaking on the linoleum, a sound that feels deafeningly loud in the sudden silence. The door creaks open further, revealing a sliver of the hallway beyond. The visual input is immediate and overwhelming: the long, empty corridor stretches out, the floor tiles reflecting the fluorescent hum above. A faint, rhythmic sound drifts through the gap\u2014a low, mechanical whirring, like a distant engine or a shifting gear. It is not a sound he recognizes, yet it triggers a primal recognition of threat.\n\nElias freezes, his body locking into a rigid posture. His vision narrows, tunneling inward until the edges of the room blur and fade into a gray haze. The white of the doorframe seems to stretch, elongating into a terrifying, infinite shaft of light. His skin prickles, a cold sweat breaking out across his palms and the back of his neck, making his fingers slick and unsteady. The smell of the room, usually neutral, now carries a sharp, metallic tang, as if the air itself is thick with ozone and fear.\n\nTime distorts. The seconds stretch into agonizing minutes. Every creak of the building, every shift in the ambient lighting, is magnified into a potential signal of danger. He can hear his own breathing, loud and wet in the quiet space, a testament to his own unraveling composure. The door remains open, a silent invitation that feels like a trap. His legs feel heavy, leaden, refusing to carry him forward or backward. The whirring sound grows slightly louder, a rhythmic countdown that he cannot escape.\n\nWith a sudden, jerky motion, Elias turns and retreats, his back pressing hard against the wall. He presses himself into the corner, curling slightly as if to make himself smaller, less visible. His eyes are wide, fixed on the gap between the door and the frame, where the shadow seems to pool. The panic is a physical weight, pressing down on his chest, making it difficult to draw a full breath. He grips the edge of the wall, his knuckles turning white, anchoring himself against the rising tide of terror. The world narrows to the sliver of light and the sound of the machine, a suffocating loop of sensory input that defines his entire existence in this moment.\n",
