      "s_instruction": "Write a tutorial using a conversational, friendly tone with informal greetings and a narrative flow that emphasizes the ease of the project for beginners.",
      "u_instruction": "Write a tutorial using a formal, technical tone with numbered lists, explicit references to diagrams, and a focus on precision and safety protocols for woodworking.",
      "s_gold": "Title: DIY Macrame Plant Hanger: A Step-by-Step Guide\n\nIntroduction:\nHey there, crafty enthusiasts! Welcome to this easy-to-follow tutorial on how to create a beautiful macrame plant hanger for your home or garden. With just a few basic materials and some simple knots, you'll be able to create a stylish and functional DIY project that's perfect for any plant lover. So let's get started!\n\nMaterials:\n\n* Cotton rope (20 yards)\n* Wooden dowel (10 inches long)\n* Scissors\n* Ruler\n* Tape measure\n* Pencil\n* Hammer\n* Nails (6)\n* Step stool or chair\n\nStep 1: Measure and Mark Your Dowel\nBefore we begin, take your wooden dowel and place it horizontally on your work surface. Using a tape measure and a pencil, measure and mark the following points:\n\n* 2 inches from one end\n* 4 inches from the other end\n* 6 inches from one end\n\nThese marks will help guide your knots as you create your macrame designs.\n\nStep 2: Create Your First Knot\nBegin by tying a square knot around the center of the dowel, using one end of the rope. Make sure the knot is tight and secure. This will be the base of your plant hanger.\n\nStep 3: Add Your Second Knot\nNow, tie a second square knot, perpendicular to the first one, about 2 inches away from the first knot. This will create the base of your first macrame panel.\n\nStep 4: Add Macrame Panels\nUsing the same technique as before, tie square knots around the dowel, spacing them evenly apart. Each panel should be about 2 inches wide and 4 inches tall. Repeat this process until you have reached the end of the dowel.\n\nStep 5: Add a Hanging Loop\nOnce you have completed all your macrame panels, tie a loop at the top of the dowel using the remaining rope. This loop will allow you to hang your plant hanger securely.\n\nStep 6: Add Finishing Touches\nTo complete your plant hanger, add some decorative knots to the ends of the rope. This will not only add a stylish touch but also help secure the knots and prevent them from coming undone.\n\nSafety Precautions:\nWhen working with rope and knots, it's important to take safety precautions to avoid injury or damage. Here are some tips to keep in mind:\n\n* Wear gloves to protect your hands from rope burns and abrasions.\n* Use a stable work surface to avoid accidents and injuries.\n* Keep loose ropes and threads away from heat sources, such as stovetops or open flames.\n* Avoid pulling or yanking on the rope too hard, as this can cause damage to the material or injury to yourself.\n\nTroubleshooting Tips:\nHere are some common mistakes to avoid when creating your macrame plant hanger:\n\n* Make sure your knots are tight and secure to prevent them from coming undone.\n* Use the correct tension when tying your knots to avoid loose or too-tight panels.\n* Keep your rope evenly taut to prevent sagging or bunching.\n\nPersonalizing Your Plant Hanger:\nTo add a personal touch to your macrame plant hanger, consider adding some decorative elements, such as beads, sequins, or tassels. You can also experiment with different knot patterns or colors to create a unique and stylish piece.\n\nConclusion:\nWith these easy-to-follow steps and helpful tips, you'll be able to create a beautiful and functional DIY macrame plant hanger that will add a touch of elegance to your home or garden. Happy crafting!",
      "u_gold": "Title: How to Build a Simple DIY Shelf Using Wood\n\nIntroduction:\nHaving a functional and stylish storage solution is crucial for any living space. Building a shelf can prove to be a cost-effective and rewarding DIY project for any novice woodworker. This tutorial provides a step-by-step guide to create a functional and attractive shelf using simple materials. \n\n1. Materials Needed:\n\t* 1-inch thick wooden board (2 * length of your desired shelf + 2 inches for the sides)\n\t* 1-inch thick wooden board (2 * width of your desired shelf + 2 inches for the sides)\n\t* Wood screws\n\t* Wall anchors\n\t* Sandpaper\n\t* Wood stain\n\t* Paintbrush\n\t* Measuring tape\n\t* Pencil\n\t* Saw (circular saw or handsaw)\n\t* Drill\n\t* Screwdriver\n2. Measure and Cut the Wood:\nMark and measure the desired dimensions for the shelf on the wooden board using a measuring tape and pencil. Cut the board to these specifications using a saw.\n\n![Diagram 1: Cutting the Wood](https://i.imgur.com/4pHcZC5.png)\n\n1. Sand the Edges:\nTo ensure a smooth finish, use sandpaper to smooth out any rough edges, uneven surfaces, or blemishes on the wood. This will also create a more even surface for paint or stain application.\n![Diagram 2: Sanding the Wood](https://i.imgur.com/V62GvJa.png)\n\n1. Stain or Paint the Wood:\nAfter sanding, apply a coat of wood stain or paint to the surface of the boards. Allow sufficient time for the stain to penetrate the wood (as per manufacturer\u2019s instructions).\n![Diagram 3: Staining the Wood](https://i.imgur.com/K6LbKtZ.png)\n\n1. Assemble the Shelf:\nLay the shelf boards flat on the workspace, ensuring that the sides are even. Place the other wooden board on top of them. Adjust the position of the boards so the sides are flush with the sides of the other boards.\n\n![Diagram 4: Assembling the Shelf](https://i.imgur.com/4H9w2ZO.png)\n\n2. Drill and Secure the Shelf:\nDrill pilot holes through the sides of the shelf and into the top and bottom boards at the marked points. Use screws to secure the shelf by driving them through the pilot holes and applying wood anchors into the wall.\n\n![Diagram 5: Screwing and Securing the Shelf](https://i.imgur.com/iYdBXjg.png)\n\n1. Test the Shelf for Stability:\nGently test the shelf to ensure it is secure and stable. Adjust the screw position if necessary.\n\n1. Clean Up:\nRemove any excess glue, sawdust, or debris from the workspace.\n\nSafety Precautions:\n* Wear safety goggles or glasses to protect your eyes while cutting and sanding the wood.\n* Never touch the uncapped screws or saw blades with bare hands.\n* Work in a well-ventilated area to avoid inhaling sawdust and fumes.\n\nTroubleshooting Tips:\n* If the shelf is not level while assembling, sand the corners of the side boards until level, or adjust the position of the boards during assembly.\n\nCommon Mistakes to Avoid:\n* Not measuring and cutting the wood precisely\n* Not sanding the edges properly, leaving rough edges\n* Failing to apply the wood stain or paint evenly\n* Not securing the shelf properly, risking instability and potential harm\n\nSuggestions for Personalization:\n* Use different types of wood or stain finishes to add variation to the shelf\n* Incorporate decorative brackets or trim to enhance the appearance of the shelf\n\nConclusion:\nBy following these detailed steps and instructions, you can create a stylish and functional shelf that will add a touch of personality to your living space. Remember to take your time, focus on precision, and prioritize safety precautions while assembling.",
      "response": "# Technical Protocol for Precision Woodworking: A Step-by-Step Guide\n\n**Document ID:** WOOD-PROC-001\n**Classification:** Standard Operating Procedure (SOP)\n**Target Audience:** Certified Woodworking Technicians and Safety-Compliant Operators\n**Objective:** To establish a rigorous, error-free methodology for executing precise joinery and surface preparation while adhering to strict safety protocols.\n\n---\n\n### 1.0 Pre-Operational Safety and Environmental Assessment\n\nPrior to the initiation of any machining or assembly sequence, the operator must verify the integrity of the workspace and personal protective equipment (PPE). Failure to adhere to these protocols constitutes a critical safety violation.\n\n1.  **Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) Verification**\n    *   Confirm the fit and seal of a full-face shield over safety glasses.\n    *   Verify the integrity of hearing protection (earplugs or earmuffs) rated for the specific decibel level of the machinery.\n    *   Ensure cut-resistant gloves are worn only when handling sharp tools; **do not** wear gloves when operating rotating machinery (e.g., table saws, planers) to prevent entanglement hazards.\n\n2.  **Workspace Sanitization and Layout**\n    *   Conduct a visual sweep of the work area to identify trip hazards, loose debris, or damaged flooring.\n    *   Ensure adequate ventilation is active to mitigate the accumulation of wood dust, which poses respiratory risks.\n    *   Verify that all power cords are routed away from high-traffic pedestrian zones and are secured to prevent tripping.\n\n3.  **Machinery Inspection**\n    *   Inspect all blades, bits, and cutting tools for signs of wear, chipping, or dullness. Replace any compromised components immediately.\n    *   Check that all machine guards are in their designated locked positions and free of obstructions.\n    *   Test the emergency stop (E-Stop) mechanism to ensure immediate responsiveness.\n\n---\n\n### 2.0 Material Preparation and Dimensional Analysis\n\nPrecision in woodworking relies on the accuracy of the raw material prior to processing. Deviations at this stage compound exponentially during subsequent operations.\n\n1.  **Dimensional Verification**\n    *   Utilize a calibrated digital caliper to measure the length, width, and thickness of the stock.\n    *   Record measurements to the nearest 0.01 mm.\n    *   **Diagram Reference:** Consult *Figure 2.1: Stock Dimensional Verification Matrix* to correlate measured values against the required tolerance limits for the specific project specification.\n\n2.  **Surface Preparation**\n    *   Remove any surface contaminants, including resin, glue, or previous machining marks, using a non-abrasive solvent compatible with the wood species.\n    *   Square the edges of the stock using a try-square and a marking gauge.\n    *   **Diagram Reference:** Refer to *Figure 2.2: Edge Squaring and Marking Protocol* for the correct angle of approach and pressure application to avoid tear-out.\n\n3.  **Clamping Strategy**\n    *   Select clamps capable of exerting a minimum of 500 N (Newtons) of force without crushing the wood fibers.\n    *   Apply clamps in a staggered pattern to distribute load evenly and prevent warping.\n    *   **Diagram Reference:** Study *Figure 2.3: Optimal Clamping Configuration* to visualize the distribution of clamping force relative to the grain direction.\n\n---\n\n### 3.0 Execution of Joinery and Machining\n\nThis phase requires strict adherence to feed rates, depth of cut, and tool path planning to ensure dimensional accuracy and tool longevity.\n\n1.  **Tool Path Planning**\n    *   Map the intended cut sequence on a digital drafting board or physical template.\n    *   Verify that the tool path does not intersect with any fixed machine components or the operator's standing zone.\n    *   **Diagram Reference:** Cross-reference the planned path with *Figure 3.1: CNC Tool Path Simulation* to identify potential collisions before physical execution.\n\n2.  **Cutting Parameters**\n    *   Set the spindle speed (RPM) according to the specific wood density and tool diameter.\n    *   Utilize a step-down depth of no more than 25% of the tool diameter to prevent tear-out and excessive heat generation.\n    *   Maintain a consistent feed rate; do not apply sudden torque spikes that may cause tool deflection.\n\n3.  **Assembly and Fit-Up**\n    *   Perform a \"dry fit\" of all joinery components without adhesive to verify clearance and alignment.\n    *   Measure critical dimensions at multiple points along the joint to ensure uniformity.\n    *   **Diagram Reference:** Examine *Figure 3.2: Joint Fit-Up Tolerance Chart* to determine acceptable variance for the specific",
