      "response": "I cannot provide a specific embed code because **you have not included the text, article, video, or media file** that you want to embed. Without the source content, there is no code to generate or share.\n\nHowever, I can provide a **detailed, step-by-step guide** on how you can locate, select, copy, and paste the embed code yourself using the standard methods found on most websites and platforms.\n\n### Step-by-Step Guide to Locating and Using an Embed Code\n\n#### Phase 1: Locating the Embed Code\nThe method depends on the type of content you are trying to embed.\n\n**Scenario A: Embedding a Video (YouTube, Vimeo, Dailymotion)**\n1.  Go to the video page on the hosting site (e.g., YouTube).\n2.  Click the **Share** button (usually near the title or description).\n3.  Select the **Embed** tab.\n4.  You will see a block of code starting with `<iframe...`.\n    *   *Note:* If you are using YouTube Studio, you can also go to the \"Embed\" tab on the video's main page to generate a custom code.\n\n**Scenario B: Embedding a Social Media Post (Facebook, Twitter/X, LinkedIn)**\n1.  Find the post you wish to embed.\n2.  Click the **Share** button.\n3.  Select **Embed** (or \"Embed Code\" on some platforms).\n4.  The platform will display the HTML snippet.\n\n**Scenario C: Embedding a Website (iFrame)**\n1.  Go to the website you want to embed.\n2.  Look for a **\"Site Map,\" \"Embed,\"** or **\"Developer Tools\"** section in the footer or header.\n3.  If available, select the specific page or section you want to embed and copy the provided code.\n    *   *Note:* Many sites do not allow embedding; if you cannot find a button, the content may be protected by copyright or technical restrictions.\n\n**Scenario D: Using the \"Insert\" Feature (No Code Required)**\n*Many modern website editors (like WordPress, Wix, Squarespace) allow you to paste a URL instead of raw code.*\n1.  In your website editor, click the **Insert** or **Add Block** button.\n2.  Search for \"Embed,\" \"Video,\" or \"Link.\"\n3.  Paste the **URL** of the content you want to embed.\n4.  The editor will automatically generate the code for you.\n\n---\n\n#### Phase 2: Selecting and Copying the Code\nOnce you have located the code block:\n\n1.  **Highlight the Code:** Click and drag your mouse cursor over the entire block of text. Ensure you select from the opening tag (e.g., `<iframe src=...`) to the closing tag (e.g., `</iframe>`).\n2.  **Copy:**\n    *   **Right-Click:** Select **Copy** from the context menu.\n    *   **Keyboard Shortcut:** Press `Ctrl + C` (Windows/Linux) or `Cmd + C` (Mac).\n    *   *Tip:* If the code is inside a text box on the website, you may need to click inside the text box first, then highlight the code within it.\n\n---\n\n#### Phase 3: Pasting into Your Website Editor\nNow, switch to the website builder or CMS where you want the content to appear.\n\n1.  **Navigate to the Editor:** Open your website in the editing mode (not the live view).\n2.  **Insert the Code:**\n    *   **Method 1 (Code Block):** Look for a button labeled **`</>`**, **`[Code]`**, **`Custom HTML`**, or **`Insert HTML`**. Click it and paste your copied code into the box.\n    *   **Method 2 (Visual Block):** If you used the \"Insert\" feature in Phase 1, simply paste the code directly into the text area of that block, or paste the URL if the editor supports it.\n3.  **Preview:** Click **Preview** or **View Live** to ensure the content displays correctly.\n4.  **Publish:** Once verified, click **Publish** or **Update** to save changes to your live site.\n\n### Troubleshooting Common Issues\n*   **Code doesn't show up:** Ensure you copied the *entire* block, including the opening and closing tags.\n*   **Content is blank:** The source website might have blocked the embed (common with news sites or social media posts that have been removed).\n*   **Layout breaks:** If the embedded content is too wide, you may need to add CSS to limit its width (e.g., `max-width: 100%;`).\n\nIf",
