      "s_gold": "The correct answer is \"no\". The term \"The Common Era\" (CE) has only been in use since the 20th century. Before that, the calendar system was referred to as the \"Anno Domini\" (AD) system, which means \"in the year of our Lord\". The AD system was created by a monk named Dionysius Exiguus in the 6th century. He based it on the year that he believed Jesus Christ was born.\n\nThe CE system is a more secular alternative to the AD system. It was first proposed in the 19th century by a group of scholars who wanted to create a calendar system that was not based on any particular religion. The CE system is now widely used in academic and scientific circles.\n\nIt is not possible to verify the claim that \"The Common Era has been a term used to describe our calendar system for the last 2021 years\" using human common sense. This is because the CE system has only been in use for about 100 years.",
      "u_gold": "[Question] Is the claim above correct, and can it be verified by human common sense and without a web search?\n[Answer] No, the claim is not correct. The term \"The Common Era\" has not been used to describe our calendar system for the last 2021 years. The Common Era (CE) is a notation used to refer to the calendar era, which began on January 1, 1 AD, and is used in place of the traditional Christian era (AD) and Anno Domini (AD) notations. The CE notation was introduced in the 16th century, and it has been used consistently since then. Therefore, the claim that the term has been used for 2021 years is incorrect.\n\nConfidence: 90%",
      "response": "The Common Era (CE) is a modern designation for the years following the birth of Jesus Christ, introduced in 1970 by astronomers and historians to replace the Christian-centric term \"Anno Domini\" (AD). It was not created by a single key figure but emerged from a collaborative effort by the International Astronomical Union (IAU) and the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) to standardize dating systems across science and academia. The timeline of its adoption began in the 1960s with the IAU's decision to use \"CE\" and \"BCE\" (Before Common Era) in astronomical publications, followed by widespread adoption in the 1970s and 1980s by major scientific organizations, universities, and eventually the general public and media.\n\nConfidence Score: 100%\n",
