      "s_gold": "There are plenty of amazing campsites in Yosemite National Park! Some popular ones include Upper Pines, Camp 4, and Half Dome. Each of these camping areas offer unique amenities and experiences that you won't find elsewhere. You can learn more about these sites by visiting the official Yosemite National Park website or researching online. What specific information are you looking for about these campsites?",
      "u_gold": "Yosemite National Park is home to many beautiful campsites, each offering a unique experience. There are 13 campgrounds within the park, but some are more popular and are often busy during peak seasons. Here are some of the best campsites in Yosemite National Park:\n\n1. Upper Pines Campground (Half Dome Village): This campground is the first one you'll come to when entering Yosemite Valley. It offers easy access to the trailhead for hiking to Half Dome. Upper Pines has several accommodation options, including tent cabins, car tent platforms (a covered canvas tent with hard floors for camping on your car), standard open campsites and their Deluxe cabins. They also have several packages you can book which include guided hikes, meals and more.\n2. Yosemite Creek Campground (Big Trees Campsites): Located in the Wawona Area of the park, next to Mariposa Grove of Giant Sequoias this site has accessible hiking trails and the opportunity to see bears in their natural habitat.\n3. Hodgdon Meadow Campground: Hodgdon Meadow is a good option for those looking for a more basic camping experience and is in a quiet area near the Big Oak Flat Entrance. It's pet-friendly and often is less busy than other campgrounds in the valley area.\n4. Bridalveil Creek Campground: This is a small, one-loop campground with 35 sites located in the Wawona area of Yosemite. It's a more secluded campground, nestled among tall trees and close to a year-round creek perfect for a day of fishing.\n5. Tuolumne Meadows Campground: Located high in the park (but not at the Hetch Hetchy Reservoir), this campground is pet-friendly and has 304 campsites near majestic meadows. It's a good base for exploring the park's higher elevation areas, such as the Lembert Dome, Elizabeth Lake, or the Tuolumne Grove of Giant Sequoias.\n\nRemember that during peak season, most of the campsites in Yosemite get booked up quickly. It's best to make a reservation in advance through the recreation.gov website or call 1-877-444-6777. Yosemite National Park has a lot more to offer than just campsites, from hiking to marveling at waterfalls and enjoying cultural events, so I would recommend spending some time researching the area and planning your trip ahead of time.",
      "response": "Here is a brief list of three popular campsites, followed by a detailed breakdown of five specific campgrounds.\n\n### Three Popular Campsites (General Overview)\n\n1.  **Yosemite Valley Campground (California, USA)**\n    Located directly within the iconic Yosemite National Park, this site offers immediate access to the valley floor, waterfalls, and granite cliffs. It is known for its rustic charm and proximity to major attractions like Half Dome and El Capitan.\n\n2.  **Glacier National Park Campground (Montana, USA)**\n    Situated in the heart of Glacier National Park, this campground provides stunning views of the Going-to-the-Sun Road and the surrounding peaks. It is famous for its proximity to the famous Grinnell Glacier and diverse wildlife viewing opportunities.\n\n3.  **Great Smoky Mountains National Park Campground (Tennessee/North Carolina, USA)**\n    Spanning the border between two states, this massive park offers several campgrounds ranging from high-elevation sites near the Appalachian Trail to lower valleys. It is renowned for its dense forests, hiking trails, and abundant birdlife.\n\n---\n\n### Five Specific Campgrounds (Detailed List)\n\n1.  **Camp 4 at Crater Lake National Park**\n    *   **Exact Location:** Crater Lake, Oregon, USA (Elevation: 6,178 ft / 1,882 m).\n    *   **Site Counts:** Approximately 100 sites (including tent, RV, and group sites).\n    *   **Unique Features:** This is the only campground in the United States located at an elevation of over 6,000 feet. It offers direct access to the rim of the lake and is the only place where you can camp while looking directly into the deepest lake in the U.S.\n\n2.  **Shenandoah National Park \u2013 Big Meadows Campground**\n    *   **Exact Location:** Big Meadows, Shenandoah National Park, Virginia, USA.\n    *   **Site Counts:** 140 sites (100 tent sites, 40 RV sites).\n    *   **Unique Features:** Located at the highest point in the park, this site is famous for its proximity to the Old Rag Mountain trail and the iconic Skyline Drive. It features a large, open meadow perfect for stargazing and is often the most visited campground in the park.\n\n3.  **Arches National Park \u2013 Devils Garden Campground**\n    *   **Exact Location:** Moab, Utah, USA (Elevation: 4,300 ft / 1,310 m).\n    *   **Site Counts:** 120 sites (100 tent sites, 20 RV sites).\n    *   **Unique Features:** Situated right at the entrance to the park's most famous area, this campground offers immediate access to Delicate Arch and the Window Rocker. It is known for its unique \"rock and dirt\" construction and is the primary hub for exploring the park's red rock formations.\n\n4.  **Olympic National Park \u2013 Hoh Rain Forest Campground**\n    *   **Exact Location:** Hoh River, Olympic National Park, Washington, USA (Elevation: 1,000 ft / 305 m).\n    *   **Site Counts:** 100 sites (all tent sites only; no RVs allowed).\n    *   **Unique Features:** Located deep within the temperate rainforest, this site is one of the wettest places in the continental U.S. It offers a unique experience with towering western hemlock trees, moss-covered rocks, and the nearby Hoh River, requiring visitors to bring rain gear and sturdy footwear.\n\n5.  **Great Sand Dunes National Park \u2013 Lower Dunes Campground**\n    *   **Exact Location:** Alamosa, Colorado, USA (Elevation: 7,000 ft / 2,133 m).\n    *   **Site Counts:** 100 sites (100 tent sites; no RVs).\n    *   **Unique Features:** This is the only campground in the U.S. National Park System located directly on a massive sand dune system. It offers a surreal landscape where the ground is composed of shifting sand, providing a distinct contrast to the rocky terrain found in most other national parks.\n",
