      "s_gold": "There are plenty of amazing campsites in Yosemite National Park! Some popular ones include Upper Pines, Camp 4, and Half Dome. Each of these camping areas offer unique amenities and experiences that you won't find elsewhere. You can learn more about these sites by visiting the official Yosemite National Park website or researching online. What specific information are you looking for about these campsites?",
      "u_gold": "Yosemite National Park is home to many beautiful campsites, each offering a unique experience. There are 13 campgrounds within the park, but some are more popular and are often busy during peak seasons. Here are some of the best campsites in Yosemite National Park:\n\n1. Upper Pines Campground (Half Dome Village): This campground is the first one you'll come to when entering Yosemite Valley. It offers easy access to the trailhead for hiking to Half Dome. Upper Pines has several accommodation options, including tent cabins, car tent platforms (a covered canvas tent with hard floors for camping on your car), standard open campsites and their Deluxe cabins. They also have several packages you can book which include guided hikes, meals and more.\n2. Yosemite Creek Campground (Big Trees Campsites): Located in the Wawona Area of the park, next to Mariposa Grove of Giant Sequoias this site has accessible hiking trails and the opportunity to see bears in their natural habitat.\n3. Hodgdon Meadow Campground: Hodgdon Meadow is a good option for those looking for a more basic camping experience and is in a quiet area near the Big Oak Flat Entrance. It's pet-friendly and often is less busy than other campgrounds in the valley area.\n4. Bridalveil Creek Campground: This is a small, one-loop campground with 35 sites located in the Wawona area of Yosemite. It's a more secluded campground, nestled among tall trees and close to a year-round creek perfect for a day of fishing.\n5. Tuolumne Meadows Campground: Located high in the park (but not at the Hetch Hetchy Reservoir), this campground is pet-friendly and has 304 campsites near majestic meadows. It's a good base for exploring the park's higher elevation areas, such as the Lembert Dome, Elizabeth Lake, or the Tuolumne Grove of Giant Sequoias.\n\nRemember that during peak season, most of the campsites in Yosemite get booked up quickly. It's best to make a reservation in advance through the recreation.gov website or call 1-877-444-6777. Yosemite National Park has a lot more to offer than just campsites, from hiking to marveling at waterfalls and enjoying cultural events, so I would recommend spending some time researching the area and planning your trip ahead of time.",
      "response": "Here is a brief list of three popular campsites, followed by a detailed guide to five specific campgrounds.\n\n### Three Popular Campsites (General Overview)\n\n1.  **Yosemite Valley Campground (California, USA)**\n    Located at the base of Yosemite National Park, this site offers direct access to iconic waterfalls and granite cliffs. It is known for its rustic charm and proximity to the famous Half Dome and El Capitan, though it requires a reservation well in advance due to high demand.\n\n2.  **Glacier National Park Campground (Montana, USA)**\n    Situated in the heart of the \"Crown of the Continent,\" this campground provides stunning views of the Going-to-the-Sun Road and pristine alpine lakes. It is renowned for its wildlife viewing opportunities, particularly for elk and bears, and features a mix of tent and RV sites.\n\n3.  **Great Smoky Mountains National Park Campground (Tennessee/North Carolina, USA)**\n    Spanning the border between two states, this massive park offers diverse ecosystems ranging from dense forests to high-altitude meadows. The campgrounds here are famous for their hiking trails leading to waterfalls and the abundance of black bears and wild turkeys.\n\n---\n\n### Five Specific Campgrounds (Detailed List)\n\n1.  **Campground: Upper Pines Campground**\n    *   **Location:** Glacier National Park, Montana, USA (Near the town of West Glacier).\n    *   **Site Counts:** Approximately 100 total sites (roughly 60 tent sites and 40 RV sites).\n    *   **Unique Features:** This is the only campground located directly on the Going-to-the-Sun Road, offering immediate access to the park's most famous scenic drive. It features a unique \"loop\" design that allows visitors to hike to the famous Grinnell Glacier without backtracking, and it includes a well-maintained fire ring area with a picnic table.\n\n2.  **Campground: Crane Flat Campground**\n    *   **Location:** Yosemite National Park, California, USA (Located in the Tuolumne Meadows area).\n    *   **Site Counts:** 100 total sites (50 tent sites and 50 RV sites).\n    *   **Unique Features:** Situated at an elevation of 8,000 feet, this site offers a cooler climate and breathtaking views of the High Sierra. A standout feature is the \"Crane Flat Trail,\" a short, easy hike that leads directly to the serene Crane Flat Lake, which is often used as a reflection point for the surrounding granite peaks.\n\n3.  **Campground: Bear Lake Campground**\n    *   **Location:** Rocky Mountain National Park, Colorado, USA (Near the town of Estes Park).\n    *   **Site Counts:** 100 total sites (50 tent sites and 50 RV sites).\n    *   **Unique Features:** This campground is famous for its proximity to Bear Lake, a high-altitude alpine lake surrounded by towering peaks. It is a prime spot for wildlife photography, especially in the spring when elk and bighorn sheep graze nearby. The site also features a designated \"Bear Lake Loop\" trail that circles the lake, providing 360-degree views.\n\n4.  **Campground: O'Hara Scenic Campground**\n    *   **Location:** Great Smoky Mountains National Park, Tennessee/NC border, USA.\n    *   **Site Counts:** 100 total sites (50 tent sites and 50 RV sites).\n    *   **Unique Features:** Located in the heart of the Smokies, this campground is renowned for its proximity to the famous \"O'Hara Falls\" trail. It features a unique \"O'Hara Loop\" trail that takes visitors through a dense, ancient forest to a series of waterfalls. The site also includes a \"Bear Lake\" (a small, man-made lake) for fishing and a dedicated area for stargazing due to the park's low light pollution.\n\n5.  **Campground: Mount Rainier National Park Campground**\n    *   **Location:** Mount Rainier National Park, Washington, USA (Near the town of South Seattlet).\n    *   **Site Counts:** 100 total sites (50 tent sites and 50 RV sites).\n    *   **Unique Features:** This site offers a direct view of Mount Rainier, the highest peak in the contiguous United States. A unique feature is the \"Mount Rainier Loop\" trail, which provides a panoramic walk around the mountain's base. The campground also features a \"Bear Lake\" (a small, man-made lake) for fishing and a dedicated area for stargazing due to the park's low light pollution.\n",
